#Some of the checks are a bit foddy, use common sense and pick the proper ones
#For some of the config applications for critical services, i will most likely make seperate config files to copy/paste

Basic System Updates and Monitoring
Update and Upgrade System Packages
  sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

Create Backups
  rsync -av --delete /path/to/data /backup/location

Read Documentation
Always check system-specific READMEs and logs before implementing changes.

Monitor Systems
Use monitoring tools:
  top
  htop
  glances

User and Authentication Management
List Local Users and Groups
  cat /etc/passwd
  cat /etc/group

Remove Unused or Unauthorized Users/Groups
  sudo deluser [username]
  sudo groupdel [groupname]

Install Password Complexity Enforcement
  sudo apt-get install libpam-cracklib
  sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-password

Set Password Policies in /etc/login.defs
  PASS_MAX_DAYS 90
  PASS_MIN_DAYS 30
  PASS_WARN_AGE 7

Configure Account Lockout Policies
  sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-auth
  Add auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=3 unlock_time=900 fail_interval=900

Enforce Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) for SSH
  sudo apt install libpam-google-authenticator
  sudo nano /etc/pam.d/sshd
  Add auth required pam_google_authenticator.so
  Enable ChallengeResponseAuthentication yes

Log and File Monitoring
Review Logs for Suspicious Activity
  cat /var/log/auth.log
  cat /var/log/syslog
  cat /var/log/messages

Use journalctl to Review System Logs
  journalctl -xe

Monitor Changes to Files with auditd
  sudo apt install auditd
  sudo service auditd start
  auditctl -w /path/to/file -p war -k keyword

Check File Integrity Using aide
  sudo apt install aide
  sudo aideinit

Check System for Rootkits
  sudo apt install chkrootkit
  sudo chkrootkit
Or:
  sudo apt install rkhunter
  sudo rkhunter --check

Network and Firewall Security
  Install and Enable GUFW Firewall
    sudo apt install gufw
    sudo gufw enable

Disable Unused or Insecure Services
  sudo systemctl stop [service]
  sudo systemctl disable [service]

Harden Network Configuration
  Enable SYN cookies:
    echo 1 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_syncookies

Disable IPv6 (if not required)
    sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf
    Add net.ipv6.conf.all.disable_ipv6 = 1
  Apply changes:
    sudo sysctl -p

Prevent IP Spoofing
  Edit /etc/host.conf
  Add order bind,hosts
  nospoof on
  
Use Fail2ban for Brute-Force Protection
  sudo apt install fail2ban
  sudo systemctl enable fail2ban
  sudo systemctl start fail2ban

Disable ICMP (Ping) Responses
  Edit /etc/sysctl.conf
  Add net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_all = 1

System Hardening and Advanced Configurations
  Secure SSH Configuration
    Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config
  Disable root login:
    PermitRootLogin no
  Limit user logins:
    AllowUsers user1 user2

Set Permissions for Sensitive Files
  chmod 600 /path/to/file

Blacklist Unnecessary Kernel Modules
  Edit /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist.conf
  Add blacklist usb-storage

Use TCP Wrappers for SSH Access Control
Add rules to /etc/hosts.allow:
  sshd: 192.168.1.100
And /etc/hosts.deny:
  sshd: ALL

Web Server and Application Security
Secure Apache2 Configuration
Enable HSTS:
  Header always set Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains"
  Set strong cipher suites:
  SSLCipherSuite HIGH:!aNULL:!MD5

Harden MySQL
  sudo mysql_secure_installation
  Restrict remote access:
  bind-address = 127.0.0.1
  log_error = /var/log/mysql/error.log

Disable Dangerous PHP Functions
Edit php.ini:
  disable_functions = exec, system

Intrusion Detection and Advanced Tools
Install and Configure Tripwire
  sudo apt install tripwire
  sudo tripwire --init
  sudo tripwire --check

Install and Configure an IDS (Snort or Suricata)
  sudo apt install snort
  sudo snort -T
